1
00:00:30,646 --> 00:00:33,774
<i>It's an important and popular fact</i>

2
00:00:33,849 --> 00:00:37,785
<i>that things are not always
what they seem. </i>

3
00:00:37,853 --> 00:00:41,653
<i>For instance, on the planet Earth,
man had always assumed</i>

4
00:00:41,757 --> 00:00:45,318
<i>that he was the most intelligent
species occupying the planet,</i>

5
00:00:45,394 --> 00:00:48,090
<i>instead of the third most intelligent. </i>

6
00:00:48,164 --> 00:00:52,658
<i>The second most intelligent creatures
were dolphins, who, curiously enough,</i>

7
00:00:52,735 --> 00:00:56,671
<i>had long known of the impending
destruction of the planet Earth. </i>

8
00:00:56,739 --> 00:00:59,071
<i>They'd made many attempts
to alert mankind,</i>

9
00:00:59,175 --> 00:01:02,167
<i>but most of their communications
were misinterpreted</i>

10
00:01:02,244 --> 00:01:05,736
<i>as amusing attempts to punch footballs
or whistle for tidbits. </i>

11
00:01:05,848 --> 00:01:10,308
<i>So they eventually decided they would
leave Earth by their own means. </i>

12
00:01:10,386 --> 00:01:13,617
<i>The last ever dolphin message
was misinterpreted</i>

13
00:01:13,689 --> 00:01:16,920
<i>as a sophisticated attempt
to do a backward somersault</i>

14
00:01:17,026 --> 00:01:20,052
<i>through a hoop, whistling
The Star-Spangled Banner.</i>

15
00:01:20,162 --> 00:01:21,891
<i>In fact, the message was this:</i>

16
00:01:21,997 --> 00:01:24,898
<i>"So long and thanks for all the fish. "</i>

17
00:04:00,856 --> 00:04:05,190
<i> The extraordinary story
of The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy</i>

18
00:04:05,294 --> 00:04:06,955
<i>begins very simply. </i>

19
00:04:07,029 --> 00:04:09,930
<i>It begins with a man. </i>

20
00:04:17,840 --> 00:04:18,966
Ooh!

21
00:04:19,108 --> 00:04:20,939
<i>An Earthman, to be precise. </i>

22
00:04:21,010 --> 00:04:22,637
<i>Who no more knows his destiny,</i>

23
00:04:22,711 --> 00:04:26,203
<i>than a tea leaf knows the history
of the East India Company. </i>

24
00:04:28,517 --> 00:04:31,315
<i>His name is Arthur Dent. </i>

25
00:04:31,387 --> 00:04:34,686
<i>He is a five-foot-eight-inch-tall
ape descendant</i>

26
00:04:34,790 --> 00:04:38,783
<i>and someone is trying to drive
a bypass through his house. </i>

27
00:04:44,099 --> 00:04:46,226
What do I want you to do about it?
Find him

28
00:04:46,335 --> 00:04:50,328
and tell him I'm currently lying
flat on my back in front of...

29
00:04:50,406 --> 00:04:51,703
Fine, I'll hold.

30
00:04:51,807 --> 00:04:54,503
You can't lie in front
of the bulldozers for ever.

31
00:04:54,576 --> 00:04:56,703
I'm game. We'll see who rusts first.

32
00:04:56,812 --> 00:05:00,111
This bypass has got to be built
and it is going to be built.

33
00:05:00,215 --> 00:05:04,242
- Why has it got to be built?
- It's a bypass.

34
00:05:04,353 --> 00:05:08,881
You've got to build bypasses. Besides,
you should've protested months ago.

35
00:05:08,991 --> 00:05:12,358
The plans have been on display
at the planning office for a year.

36
00:05:12,428 --> 00:05:15,124
On display?
I had to go down to a cellar.

37
00:05:15,230 --> 00:05:20,566
Mr. Dent, have you any idea how much
damage this bulldozer would suffer

38
00:05:20,636 --> 00:05:23,104
if I just let it roll straight over you?

39
00:05:24,306 --> 00:05:27,298
- How much?
- None at all.

40
00:05:27,376 --> 00:05:30,209
<i> By a strange coincidence,
none at all</i>

41
00:05:30,279 --> 00:05:34,010
<i>is exactly how much suspicion
ape-descendant Arthur had</i>

42
00:05:34,083 --> 00:05:35,880
<i>that one of his closest friends</i>

43
00:05:35,951 --> 00:05:39,648
<i>was not descended from an ape,
but was, in fact, from a small planet</i>

44
00:05:39,722 --> 00:05:43,055
<i>somewhere in the vicinity of Betelgeuse. </i>

45
00:05:43,826 --> 00:05:46,351
Arthur! Arthur!

46
00:05:46,428 --> 00:05:48,225
- Ford!
- Yes?

47
00:05:48,297 --> 00:05:49,764
Here.

48
00:05:49,832 --> 00:05:51,231
Ah, there you are!

49
00:05:51,300 --> 00:05:53,131
Eat, drink. We gotta talk.

50
00:05:53,202 --> 00:05:56,433
Now's not the best time.
They're going to demolish my home.

51
00:05:56,505 --> 00:06:00,942
Whoa! You already...
You already know? How?

52
00:06:01,043 --> 00:06:02,943
What do you m...?

53
00:06:04,680 --> 00:06:07,808
Oh, they, they? When you say
"they" you mean they? Got it.

54
00:06:07,883 --> 00:06:12,582
Listen. I got somethin' important
I gotta tell you. Right now.

55
00:06:12,654 --> 00:06:15,122
Well, what about my house?

56
00:06:19,628 --> 00:06:25,123
Workers of the Earth, I bring
good tidings of peanuts and beer!

57
00:06:35,677 --> 00:06:37,542
- Good. Let's go to the pub.
- Huh?

58
00:06:37,613 --> 00:06:40,582
They won't demolish it
until they've finished the beers.

59
00:06:40,682 --> 00:06:43,082
- Can we trust 'em?
- To the end of the Earth.

60
00:06:43,218 --> 00:06:45,550
- How far's that?
- About 12 minutes away.

61
00:06:45,654 --> 00:06:46,678
Huh?

62
00:06:46,789 --> 00:06:48,790
Barman, six pints of bitter and quickly.
The world's about to end.

63
00:06:48,825 --> 00:06:50,791
Barman, six pints of bitter and quickly.
The world's about to end.

64
00:06:50,859 --> 00:06:52,759
Six pints coming up.

65
00:06:52,861 --> 00:06:56,524
Keep the change.
You got about ten minutes to spend it.

66
00:06:56,632 --> 00:06:59,965
Three pints each? At lunchtime?

67
00:07:07,042 --> 00:07:11,536
Sorry. Ah. Time is an illusion.

68
00:07:11,613 --> 00:07:13,740
Lunchtime, doubly so.

69
00:07:13,849 --> 00:07:17,683
And eat those peanuts,
because you'll need the salt.

70
00:07:17,753 --> 00:07:20,415
- Look, what is going on, Ford?
- Arthur...

71
00:07:22,558 --> 00:07:26,050
What if I told you
I really wasn't from Guildford?

72
00:07:26,128 --> 00:07:30,531
I was from a small planet
somewhere in the vicinity of Betelgeuse?

73
00:07:30,632 --> 00:07:32,725
Is that something
you're likely to say?

74
00:07:32,801 --> 00:07:34,166
Remember when we met?

75
00:07:41,176 --> 00:07:42,336
Out the way!

76
00:07:42,411 --> 00:07:47,007
- Oof!
- Hi.

77
00:07:47,082 --> 00:07:50,108
Wasn't it strange I was trying
to shake hands with a car?

78
00:07:50,185 --> 00:07:51,743
I assumed you were drunk.

79
00:07:51,854 --> 00:07:55,915
I thought cars were the dominant
life form. I was introducing myself.

80
00:07:56,024 --> 00:08:00,461
You saved my life. And now
I'm saving yours. Please drink.

81
00:08:00,529 --> 00:08:03,862
It must be Thursday. I could never get
the hang of Thursdays.

82
00:08:03,966 --> 00:08:07,333
- If this is about your house...
- No, it's not about the house.

83
00:08:11,340 --> 00:08:13,433
- Who's he?
- She. She.

84
00:08:13,508 --> 00:08:17,171
Tricia McMillan.
We met at a fancy-dress party.

85
00:08:18,580 --> 00:08:20,673
<i> I hate those kind of parties. </i>

86
00:08:20,782 --> 00:08:23,683
<i>I'd rather have stayed at home
and ironed my hankies. </i>

87
00:08:23,752 --> 00:08:25,913
<i>- But there I was. 
- Who are you?</i>

88
00:08:26,021 --> 00:08:27,750
<i>- Oh!
- And there she was. </i>

89
00:08:27,823 --> 00:08:32,556
- Uh, Dent. Arthur Dent.
- Oh, no. I mean, who are you?

90
00:08:32,628 --> 00:08:35,893
Oh, the costume? Right.
"Livingstone, I presume!"

91
00:08:37,032 --> 00:08:41,401
Yeah, it's not as clever as Darwin,
but the best I could do at short notice.

92
00:08:41,470 --> 00:08:43,495
You're the first to get that right.

93
00:08:43,605 --> 00:08:46,403
- Really?
- Yes. Everyone calls me Santa.

94
00:08:46,475 --> 00:08:49,000
- Right.
- I thought the beagle was a giveaway.

95
00:08:49,111 --> 00:08:50,738
So did I.

96
00:08:50,812 --> 00:08:53,246
People at these parties
are drunken idiots.

97
00:08:53,315 --> 00:08:54,748
What?

98
00:08:54,816 --> 00:08:59,185
All these people are idiots!
God!

99
00:09:01,256 --> 00:09:02,985
That's awkward.

100
00:09:03,058 --> 00:09:04,855
Tell me.

101
00:09:06,762 --> 00:09:09,526
She was amazing though, Ford.

102
00:09:09,631 --> 00:09:12,623
<i>Beautiful, witty, mad as a balloon. </i>

103
00:09:12,701 --> 00:09:17,331
Uh, without the beard,
you look at least 80 years younger.

104
00:09:17,439 --> 00:09:20,169
Maybe I'm de-evolving.

105
00:09:22,978 --> 00:09:25,845
Well, I should tell you
that I do not date

106
00:09:25,914 --> 00:09:28,644
single-celled organisms, okay?

107
00:09:31,353 --> 00:09:33,548
Let's go somewhere.

108
00:09:33,622 --> 00:09:37,786
Yeah. Definitely.
Um, where do you have in mind?

109
00:09:37,859 --> 00:09:41,818
- Madagascar.
- Is that that new club on Dean Street?

110
00:09:41,897 --> 00:09:45,230
No, it's a country
off the coast of Africa.

111
00:09:45,334 --> 00:09:48,303
That Madagascar?
Why are we waiting here?

112
00:09:48,904 --> 00:09:51,429
Wait a sec.

113
00:09:51,506 --> 00:09:53,064
Go.

114
00:09:56,211 --> 00:10:00,705
God, you're serious.
Um, I can't go to Madagascar.

115
00:10:00,816 --> 00:10:03,842
- Why not?
- Because, I just, you know...

116
00:10:03,919 --> 00:10:05,318
- You're serious?
- Yeah.

117
00:10:05,387 --> 00:10:09,050
I want to go somewhere I've never been
and I'd like to go with you, so...

118
00:10:09,124 --> 00:10:11,820
...what do you say, Dr Livingstone?

119
00:10:12,995 --> 00:10:17,762
I say that's
an extraordinary proposition.

120
00:10:17,866 --> 00:10:20,858
I can't go. I mean, I've got a job.

121
00:10:20,969 --> 00:10:23,199
Quit. Get a new one
when you come back.

122
00:10:23,305 --> 00:10:25,296
I don't even know your real name.
Ow! Ow!

123
00:10:25,407 --> 00:10:28,740
- Tricia McMillan.
- Well, Tricia McMillan.

124
00:10:28,810 --> 00:10:32,246
Um, I have a proposition for you.

125
00:10:32,347 --> 00:10:39,253
Why don't we go somewhere
a little closer first, say Cornwall,

126
00:10:39,321 --> 00:10:43,257
and we'll see how it goes.

127
00:10:43,325 --> 00:10:47,887
Right, of course, Cornwall.

128
00:10:47,963 --> 00:10:50,193
Hey, excuse me.

129
00:10:53,101 --> 00:10:54,591
Is this guy boring you?

130
00:10:54,669 --> 00:10:57,229
Why don't you talk to me instead?

131
00:10:57,305 --> 00:11:00,604
I'm from a different planet.

132
00:11:03,278 --> 00:11:06,441
It's true. You want to see my spaceship?

133
00:11:07,949 --> 00:11:11,612
"Do you want to see my spaceship?"
What kind of chat-up line is that?

134
00:11:11,720 --> 00:11:14,883
Mm, that does happen.

135
00:11:14,956 --> 00:11:17,925
Speaking of...

136
00:11:18,026 --> 00:11:20,290
We've got two minutes.
Drink up.

137
00:11:20,395 --> 00:11:22,363
That's my house.

138
00:11:30,138 --> 00:11:34,199
People of Earth, a round of drinks,
for everyone, on me.

139
00:11:34,276 --> 00:11:36,972
You really think
the world's going to end?

140
00:11:37,045 --> 00:11:38,569
Yes.

141
00:11:38,647 --> 00:11:43,107
Shouldn't we lie down, or put a paper
bag over our heads, or something?

142
00:11:43,218 --> 00:11:46,153
- If you like.
- Will it help?

143
00:11:46,221 --> 00:11:48,917
Not at all. See you.

144
00:11:48,990 --> 00:11:50,218
Last orders!

145
00:12:06,575 --> 00:12:08,873
- What is that?
- Run!

146
00:12:08,944 --> 00:12:10,912
Look out!

147
00:12:38,507 --> 00:12:39,769
Aha! Towel!

148
00:12:41,843 --> 00:12:43,834
Arthur!

149
00:12:43,912 --> 00:12:45,880
What the hell are those things?

150
00:12:45,981 --> 00:12:49,508
Yeow! They're ships
from a Vogon constructor fleet.

151
00:12:49,584 --> 00:12:52,781
I picked up their signal this morning.
You'll need this.

152
00:12:54,256 --> 00:12:57,384
- What are you doing?
- We're hitching a ride.

153
00:13:00,629 --> 00:13:02,221
Um, people of Earth,

154
00:13:02,330 --> 00:13:07,768
this is Prostetnic Vogon Jeltz of the
Galactic Hyperspace Planning Council.

155
00:13:07,836 --> 00:13:09,428
As you are probably aware,

156
00:13:09,504 --> 00:13:13,099
plans for the development of the
outlying regions of the galaxy

157
00:13:13,208 --> 00:13:17,736
involve the building of a hyperspace
express route through your star system.

158
00:13:17,846 --> 00:13:22,010
<i>And your planet is one of those
scheduled for demolition. </i>

159
00:13:30,058 --> 00:13:32,549
<i>There's no point
acting surprised about it. </i>

160
00:13:32,627 --> 00:13:35,152
<i>The plans have been on display</i>

161
00:13:35,263 --> 00:13:38,994
<i>at your local planning office
in Alpha Centauri for 50 Earth years. </i>

162
00:13:40,168 --> 00:13:43,865
<i>If you can't be bothered with
local affairs, that's your lookout. </i>

163
00:13:43,939 --> 00:13:46,407
Apathetic bloody planet.

164
00:13:46,474 --> 00:13:49,500
I've no sympathy at all.

165
00:15:36,918 --> 00:15:40,115
The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy

166
00:15:40,188 --> 00:15:42,179
<i>is a wholly remarkable book. </i>

167
00:15:42,257 --> 00:15:45,522
<i>Perhaps the most remarkable,
certainly the most successful,</i>

168
00:15:45,593 --> 00:15:49,689
<i>ever to come out of the great publishing
corporations of Ursa Minor. </i>

169
00:15:49,764 --> 00:15:53,063
<i>More popular than
The Celestial Homecare Omnibus,</i>

170
00:15:53,168 --> 00:15:56,934
<i>better selling than
53 More Things to Do in Zero Gravity,</i>

171
00:15:57,038 --> 00:16:00,030
<i>and more controversial than
Oolon Colluphid's trilogy</i>

172
00:16:00,108 --> 00:16:03,271
<i>of philosophical blockbusters,
Where God Went Wrong,</i>

173
00:16:03,378 --> 00:16:05,869
Some More of God's Greatest Mistakes,

174
00:16:05,947 --> 00:16:08,279
<i>and Who Is This God Person Anyway?</i>

175
00:16:09,150 --> 00:16:12,085
<i>It's already supplanted
the Encyclopedia Galactica</i>

176
00:16:12,187 --> 00:16:15,156
<i>as the standard repository
of all knowledge and wisdom</i>

177
00:16:15,223 --> 00:16:17,817
<i>for two important reasons. </i>

178
00:16:17,892 --> 00:16:20,486
<i>First, it's slightly cheaper,</i>

179
00:16:20,595 --> 00:16:23,689
<i>and second, it has the words
"Don't Panic"</i>

180
00:16:23,765 --> 00:16:27,257
<i>printed in large,
friendly letters on its cover. </i>

181
00:16:35,877 --> 00:16:38,675
So you're not from Guildford?

182
00:16:38,813 --> 00:16:42,874
Which would explain the accent,
which I've always wondered about.

183
00:16:42,951 --> 00:16:46,751
Um, you're not an out-of-work actor,

184
00:16:46,821 --> 00:16:52,282
but rather a writer for this,
this book thing.

185
00:16:52,360 --> 00:16:54,794
Good, huh?

186
00:16:54,863 --> 00:16:57,297
I don't feel well.
I need a cup of tea.

187
00:16:57,365 --> 00:17:00,766
If I asked where we were,
would I regret it?

188
00:17:00,869 --> 00:17:04,100
- We're safe for now.
- Good.

189
00:17:04,205 --> 00:17:08,039
We're in the washroom on one of the
ships of the Vogon constructor fleet.

190
00:17:08,143 --> 00:17:11,635
- Oh, get me home, Ford.
- Arthur, your home is...

191
00:17:11,746 --> 00:17:16,308
Oh, God, my home.
My home was demolished.

192
00:17:21,189 --> 00:17:24,056
You don't remember.

193
00:17:24,159 --> 00:17:30,496
Okay, Arthur, I've got something to tell
you. It's unfortunate, but it's true.

194
00:17:30,565 --> 00:17:33,762
Your home planet has been blown up.

195
00:17:42,610 --> 00:17:46,444
Huh, blown up.

196
00:17:51,519 --> 00:17:53,510
Couldn't you have done something?

197
00:17:53,588 --> 00:17:57,615
I saved your life.
Okay, that makes us even.

198
00:17:57,725 --> 00:18:01,661
It's a tough galaxy. If you want
to survive out here, you've...

199
00:18:01,763 --> 00:18:05,392
...gotta know where your towel is.

200
00:18:05,467 --> 00:18:07,992
Okay, give me a hand over here.

201
00:18:10,438 --> 00:18:14,465
Careful. It's hot.
We've gotta get off this ship.

202
00:18:14,542 --> 00:18:16,635
Before the Vogons find us.

203
00:18:16,711 --> 00:18:19,737
Vogons, they hate hitchhikers. Pull.

204
00:18:19,848 --> 00:18:23,147
Huh?

205
00:18:25,553 --> 00:18:28,886
- Now we'll get a signal.
- What is a Vogon?

206
00:18:28,990 --> 00:18:30,821
Ask the Guide. Say "Vogons".

207
00:18:31,559 --> 00:18:34,653
Vogons.

208
00:18:35,463 --> 00:18:39,866
<i> Vogons are one of the
most unpleasant races in the galaxy. </i>

209
00:18:39,934 --> 00:18:44,268
<i>Not evil, but bad-tempered,
bureaucratic, officious and callous. </i>

210
00:18:44,339 --> 00:18:47,866
<i>They wouldn't even lift a finger
to save their own grandmothers</i>

211
00:18:47,942 --> 00:18:51,207
<i>from the Ravenous Bugblatter Beast
of Traal without orders</i>

212
00:18:51,279 --> 00:18:53,747
<i>signed in triplicate,
sent in, sent back,</i>

213
00:18:53,815 --> 00:18:57,148
<i>queried, lost, found,
subjected to public inquiry,</i>

214
00:18:57,285 --> 00:19:00,686
<i>lost again and finally buried
in soft peat for three months</i>

215
00:19:00,755 --> 00:19:03,588
<i>and recycled as firelighters. </i>

216
00:19:04,926 --> 00:19:09,727
<i>On no account should you allow
a Vogon to read poetry to you. </i>

217
00:19:11,366 --> 00:19:15,962
They can't think or imagine.
Most can't spell. They just run things.

218
00:19:19,107 --> 00:19:20,631
Hmm?

219
00:19:22,277 --> 00:19:24,268
And if we don't get a ride soon,

220
00:19:24,379 --> 00:19:27,780
we won't need the Guide to tell us
how unpleasant the Vogons are.

221
00:19:27,849 --> 00:19:30,215
They've already destroyed
a planet today.

222
00:19:30,285 --> 00:19:32,617
That always makes them a little eee!

223
00:19:37,025 --> 00:19:39,687
Ughh! What is that?

224
00:19:39,761 --> 00:19:42,787
- Put this in your ear.
- Huh?

225
00:19:46,568 --> 00:19:50,436
<i> We have unwittingly
picked up a couple of hitchhikers. </i>

226
00:19:50,505 --> 00:19:53,201
The fish is translating for you.

227
00:19:54,175 --> 00:19:57,303
<i> The Babel fish
is small, yellow, leech-like,</i>

228
00:19:57,378 --> 00:20:01,747
<i>and probably the oddest thing
in the universe. </i>

